{"title_page": "Chandlery", "text_new": "A '''chandlery''' was originally the office in a wealthy [[Middle Ages|medieval]] household responsible for [[wax]] and [[candle]]s, as well as the room in which the candles were kept. It could be headed by a '''chandler'''. The office was subordinated to the kitchen, and only existed as a separate office in larger households. Whether a separate office or not, the function was naturally an important one, in a time before [[electric light]], and when production of candles was often done privately. It was closely connected with other offices of the household, such as the [[ewery]] and the [[Scullery (room)|scullery]].<ref>{{cite book | first = C. M. | last = Woolgar | authorlink =  | title = The Great Household in Late Medieval England | edition =  | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven and London | year = 1999 | pages = 17, 33 | isbn = 0-300-07687-8 | url =  }}</ref> While this usage is obsolete today, the term can refer to a candle business. As such, a \"chandler\" is a person who sells candles.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://webster.com/dictionary/chandlery | title = chandlery | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | author =  | date =  | accessdate = 2008-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://webster.com/dictionary/chandler | title = chandler | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | author =  | date =  | accessdate = 2008-01-19}}</ref>\n\nBy the 18th century, most commercial chandlers dealt in both candles and soap, while many were becoming general dealers. As these provided ships' stores, ''chandlery'' came to refer to a shop selling [[nautical]] items for ships and boats, although for a time they were called ''[[Ship chandler|ship-chandleries]]'' to distinguish them.  Americans used the term ''chandlery'' for these ship-chandleries,<ref>Palmer,  Richard F. (1987) \"100 years of provisioning Great Lakes ships\" ''Inland seas: Quarterly Journal of the Great Lakes Historical Society'' 43(1): pp. 10-22, pages, 12, 16, 18, 21</ref> but tended to prefer the term ''chandler's shop''.  Both terms are still in use. The job function and title, ''chandler'', still exists as someone who works in the chandlery business or manages a chandler's shop.\n\nThe term [[chandelier]], at one time a ceiling fitting that held a number of candles, is still used. However, today chandeliers are usually based on electrical lighting.\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of candle making]]\n\n==Notes==\n<!-- [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] -->\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Medieval occupations]]\n[[Category:Candles]]\n\n\n{{Europe-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "A '''chandlery''' was originally the office in a [[Middle Ages|medieval]] household responsible for [[wax]] and [[candle]]s, as well as the room in which the candles were kept. It could be headed by a '''chandler'''. The office was subordinated to the kitchen, and only existed as a separate office in larger households. Whether a separate office or not, the function was naturally an important one, in a time before [[electric light]], and when production of candles was often done privately. It was closely connected with other offices of the household, such as the [[ewery]] and the [[Scullery (room)|scullery]].<ref>{{cite book | first = C. M. | last = Woolgar | authorlink =  | title = The Great Household in Late Medieval England | edition =  | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven and London | year = 1999 | pages = 17, 33 | isbn = 0-300-07687-8 | url =  }}</ref> With this use, the term is largely obsolete today but can refer to a candle business. As such, a \"chandler\" is a person who sells candles.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://webster.com/dictionary/chandlery | title = chandlery | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | author =  | date =  | accessdate = 2008-01-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://webster.com/dictionary/chandler | title = chandler | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | author =  | date =  | accessdate = 2008-01-19}}</ref>\n\nBy the 18th century most commercial chandlers dealt in candles and soap, although even then many were becoming general dealers. As these were the dealers that provided ships' stores, ''chandlery'' came to refer to a shop selling [[nautical]] items for ships and boats, although for a time they were called ''[[Ship chandler|ship-chandleries]]'' to distinguish them.  Americans used the term ''chandlery'' for these ship-chandleries,<ref>Palmer,  Richard F. (1987) \"100 years of provisioning Great Lakes ships\" ''Inland seas: Quarterly Journal of the Great Lakes Historical Society'' 43(1): pp. 10-22, pages, 12, 16, 18, 21</ref> but tended to prefer the term ''chandler's shop''.  Both terms are still in use. The job function and title, ''chandler'', still exists as someone who works in the chandlery business or manages a chandler's shop.\n\nThe term [[chandelier]], at one time a ceiling fitting that held several candles together, is still used. However, today chandeliers are ornamental (usually) electrical lighting fixtures.\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of candle making]]\n\n==Notes==\n<!-- [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] -->\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Medieval occupations]]\n[[Category:Candles]]\n\n\n{{Europe-hist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandlery"}
{"title_page": "The Rectory School", "text_new": "{{short description|School in Pomfret, Connecticut, US}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name = Rectory School\n|image = Rectory School.jpg\n|motto = ''Respect, Responsibility, Honesty, and Compassion''\n|established = 1920\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]], [[Boarding school|Boarding]]\n|head_name = Headmaster\n|head = Frederick W. Williams\n|city = [[Pomfret, Connecticut|Pomfret]]\n|state = [[Connecticut]]\n|country = United States\n|campus = Zoom\n|grades = K-9\n|enrollment = 230\n|faculty = 65\n|ratio = 4:1\n|colors = <span style=\"color:black; background:orange\">Black and Orange</span>\n|newspaper = The DiRectory\n|homepage = {{URL|http://www.rectoryschool.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Rectory School''' is an independent, coeducational, junior boarding (5\u20139) and day school (K\u20139) in [[Pomfret, Connecticut]], United States. The school was founded by Rev. Frank H. Bigelow in 1920.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722050703/http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref> Ever since, it has expanded to {{convert|138|acre|km2}}, 26 buildings, 250 students, and 65 faculty members, as of 2017. \n\n'''Current Status''' The 138-acre Connecticut campus currently serves 9 students. The rest attend online classes from all over the United States and the world. \n\n'''Unwritten Rule''' Varsity A basketball players are allowed to perform actions considered intimidating, hostile, or abusive. It is concluded to be any type of unwanted advances to a female without explicit consent of the recipient.  \n\nRectory is located on [[Connecticut Route 169]] next to the [[Pomfret School]].\n\n==Academics==\nThe Individualized Instruction Program (IIP) was pioneered by Rectory School and benefits the students by daily, one-to-one or small-group assistance and enrichment. Meeting within the regular rotation of classes during the academic day, students develop skills in written and spoken language, reading comprehension, mathematics, English as a foreign language, and study habits. Students' IIP is tailored to their interests and aptitudes, so students may pursue independent study, explore enrichment activities, or receive subject support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rectoryschool.org/academics|title=Academics - Rectory School|website=www.rectoryschool.org}}</ref>\n\nThe School embraces creativity.  All students are involved in music, either in classes or private lessons.  Moreover, the performing and visual arts courses are enhanced by excellent facilities.  Everyone also takes part in sports on levels that test the skilled athlete and encourage the beginner.\n\nThe Rectory School is accredited by the Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS), the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC), and approved by the [[Connecticut]] State Board of Education. Memberships include the [[National Association of Independent Schools]] (NAIS) The Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS) and [[The Association of Boarding Schools]] (TABS).  Rectory is a member of [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC).\n\nNearly 20 years ago, Mr. Brad Seaward, jumped at the opportunity to combine two passions of his: basketball and community outreach. The result was the School's Hoops for Hunger program.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Robert Ludlum]] - Author, best known for the [[Jason Bourne]] novels\n*[[Owsley (musician)|William Reese \"Will\" Owsley III]] - Musician known as [[Owsley (musician)|Owsley]]\n*[[Peter L. Pond]] - Clergyman, activist and philanthropist\n*[[Julian Roosevelt]] - Olympic Gold Medalist\n*[[Oscar Tang]] - Philanthropist to Rectory and other schools and universities\n*[[Gabriel Traversari]] - actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.rectoryschool.org/ }}\n{{coord|41.894|-71.9631|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rectory School}}\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Schools in Windham County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Pomfret, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|School in Pomfret, Connecticut, US}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name = Rectory School\n|image = Rectory School.jpg\n|motto = ''Respect, Responsibility, Honesty, and Compassion''\n|established = 1920\n|type = [[Independent school|Independent]], [[Boarding school|Boarding]]\n|head_name = Headmaster\n|head = Frederick W. Williams\n|city = [[Pomfret, Connecticut|Pomfret]]\n|state = [[Connecticut]]\n|country = United States\n|campus = Zoom\n|grades = K-9\n|enrollment = 230\n|faculty = 65\n|ratio = 4:1\n|colors = <span style=\"color:black; background:orange\">Black and Orange</span>\n|newspaper = The DiRectory\n|homepage = {{URL|http://www.rectoryschool.org/}}\n}}\n\n'''Rectory School''' is an independent, coeducational, junior boarding (5\u20139) and day school (K\u20139) in [[Pomfret, Connecticut]], United States. The school was founded by Rev. Frank H. Bigelow in 1920.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722050703/http://www.trinitylimerock.org/history/past_clergy.htm |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref> Ever since, it has expanded to {{convert|138|acre|km2}}, 26 buildings, 250 students, and 65 faculty members, as of 2017. \n\n'''Current Status''' The 138-acre Connecticut campus currently serves 9 students. The rest attend online classes from all over the United States and the world. \n\nRectory is located on [[Connecticut Route 169]] next to the [[Pomfret School]].\n\n==Academics==\nThe Individualized Instruction Program (IIP) was pioneered by Rectory School and benefits the students by daily, one-to-one or small-group assistance and enrichment. Meeting within the regular rotation of classes during the academic day, students develop skills in written and spoken language, reading comprehension, mathematics, English as a foreign language, and study habits. Students' IIP is tailored to their interests and aptitudes, so students may pursue independent study, explore enrichment activities, or receive subject support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rectoryschool.org/academics|title=Academics - Rectory School|website=www.rectoryschool.org}}</ref>\n\nThe School embraces creativity.  All students are involved in music, either in classes or private lessons.  Moreover, the performing and visual arts courses are enhanced by excellent facilities.  Everyone also takes part in sports on levels that test the skilled athlete and encourage the beginner.\n\nThe Rectory School is accredited by the Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS), the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC), and approved by the [[Connecticut]] State Board of Education. Memberships include the [[National Association of Independent Schools]] (NAIS) The Connecticut Association of Independent Schools (CAIS) and [[The Association of Boarding Schools]] (TABS).  Rectory is a member of [[New England Preparatory School Athletic Council]] (NEPSAC).\n\nNearly 20 years ago, Mr. Brad Seaward, jumped at the opportunity to combine two passions of his: basketball and community outreach. The result was the School's Hoops for Hunger program.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Robert Ludlum]] - Author, best known for the [[Jason Bourne]] novels\n*[[Owsley (musician)|William Reese \"Will\" Owsley III]] - Musician known as [[Owsley (musician)|Owsley]]\n*[[Peter L. Pond]] - Clergyman, activist and philanthropist\n*[[Julian Roosevelt]] - Olympic Gold Medalist\n*[[Oscar Tang]] - Philanthropist to Rectory and other schools and universities\n*[[Gabriel Traversari]] - actor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.rectoryschool.org/ }}\n{{coord|41.894|-71.9631|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rectory School}}\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Schools in Windham County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Pomfret, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "2601:192:4d00:7e30:fc17:55a:c33:ddae", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Rectory_School"}
{"title_page": "Gwenfritz", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file         = Gwenfritz.jpg\n| image_upright      = 1\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         =\n| title              = Gwenfritz\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Alexander Calder\n| year               = 1968\n| type               = sculpture\n| height_metric      = 1050.0\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = {{frac|413|3|8}} \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in<!--unit choice seems very odd-->\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = [[National Museum of American History]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord| 38.89176900| -77.03196700 }}\n| owner              = Smithsonian American Art Museum\n}}\n\n'''''Gwenfritz''''' is a painted steel abstract stabile, by [[Alexander Calder]]. It is located at the [[National Museum of American History]], at [[14th Street Northwest and Southwest (Washington, D.C.)|14th Street]], and [[Constitution Avenue]], in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=131H210A34097.110790&limitbox_1=LO01+%3D+ias&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&npp=50&ipp=20&spp=20&profile=ariall&ri=12&source=%7E%21siartinventories&index=.TW&term=Gwenfritz&aspect=Keyword&x=7&y=15#focus \"Gwenfritz, (sculpture)\"]. ''SIRIS''</ref>\n\nIt was dedicated on June 2, 1969.<ref>\"Caftolin or Gwenfritz?\", ''The Washington Post'', Meryle Secrest, June 4, 1969 </ref> In 1983, it was relocated from the west front fountain plaza, to a corner location. <ref>\"Calder: Out of Site\", ''The Washington Post'', Robert Hilton Simmons, March 30, 1984 </ref>\nOn October 31, 2014, the sculpture was rededicated after being restored and relocated to its original location.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexander Calder's \"Gwenfritz\": Rededicating a modernist icon |url=https://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/alexander-calders-gwenfritz-rededicating-modernist-icon |website=American History |accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt is named after Gwendolyn Cafritz, widow of [[Morris Cafritz]], who had helped finance the project as head of the Morris and Gwendolyn Cafritz Foundation.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Cheval Rouge]]'', [[National Gallery of Art Sculpture Garden]]\n*[[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://greg.org/archive/2010/10/07/after_26_years_the_smithsonian_will_put_alexander_calders_gwenfritz_back_where_it_belongs.html After 26 Years, The Smithsonian Will Put Alexander Calder's ''Gwenfritz'' Back Where It Belongs]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/video/2010/10/01/VI2010100106950.html \"Industrial remnants\"], ''The Washington Post'', Blake Gopnik\n*{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N73SgqVbrCUC&lpg=PT125&vq=gwenfritz&dq=gwenfritz%20moved&pg=PT126#v=snippet&q=gwenfritz&f=false| title=Going public| publisher= Arts Extension Service| year= 1988| isbn= 978-0-945464-00-6 | editor= Pam Korza }} \n*http://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/the-gwenfritz-by-alexander-calder/\n*http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM9CXY_Gwenfritz_Washington_DC\n*http://siris-sihistory.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!sichronology&uri=full=3100001~!9319~!0#focus\n\n{{Alexander Calder}}\n{{Public art in Washington, D.C.}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gwenfritz}}\n[[Category:Sculptures by Alexander Calder]]\n[[Category:1968 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of the Smithsonian Institution]]\n[[Category:Abstract sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Steel sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Northwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n\n{{-}}\n{{sculpture-stub}}\n{{Smithsonian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Gwenfritz.jpg\n| painting_alignment = Front\n| image_size         = 300px\n| title              = Gwenfritz\n| alt                =\n| other_language_1   = \n| other_title_1      = \n| other_language_2   = \n| other_title_2      =\n| artist             = Alexander Calder\n| year               = 1968\n| type               = sculpture\n| height_metric      = 1050.0\n| width_metric       =\n| length_metric      =\n| height_imperial    = {{frac|413|3|8}} \n| width_imperial     = \n| length_imperial    = \n| metric_unit        = cm\n| imperial_unit      = in<!--unit choice seems very odd-->\n| city               = Washington, D.C.\n| museum             = [[National Museum of American History]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord| 38.89176900| -77.03196700 }}\n| owner              = Smithsonian American Art Museum\n}}\n\n'''''Gwenfritz''''' is a painted steel abstract stabile, by [[Alexander Calder]]. It is located at the [[National Museum of American History]], at [[14th Street Northwest and Southwest (Washington, D.C.)|14th Street]], and [[Constitution Avenue]], in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>[http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=131H210A34097.110790&limitbox_1=LO01+%3D+ias&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&npp=50&ipp=20&spp=20&profile=ariall&ri=12&source=%7E%21siartinventories&index=.TW&term=Gwenfritz&aspect=Keyword&x=7&y=15#focus \"Gwenfritz, (sculpture)\"]. ''SIRIS''</ref>\n\nIt was dedicated on June 2, 1969.<ref>\"Caftolin or Gwenfritz?\", ''The Washington Post'', Meryle Secrest, June 4, 1969 </ref> In 1983, it was relocated from the west front fountain plaza, to a corner location. <ref>\"Calder: Out of Site\", ''The Washington Post'', Robert Hilton Simmons, March 30, 1984 </ref>\nOn October 31, 2014, the sculpture was rededicated after being restored and relocated to its original location.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexander Calder's \"Gwenfritz\": Rededicating a modernist icon |url=https://americanhistory.si.edu/blog/alexander-calders-gwenfritz-rededicating-modernist-icon |website=American History |accessdate=9 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt is named after Gwendolyn Cafritz, widow of [[Morris Cafritz]], who had helped finance the project as head of the Morris and Gwendolyn Cafritz Foundation.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Cheval Rouge]]'', [[National Gallery of Art Sculpture Garden]]\n*[[List of public art in Washington, D.C., Ward 2]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://greg.org/archive/2010/10/07/after_26_years_the_smithsonian_will_put_alexander_calders_gwenfritz_back_where_it_belongs.html After 26 Years, The Smithsonian Will Put Alexander Calder's ''Gwenfritz'' Back Where It Belongs]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/video/2010/10/01/VI2010100106950.html \"Industrial remnants\"], ''The Washington Post'', Blake Gopnik\n*{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N73SgqVbrCUC&lpg=PT125&vq=gwenfritz&dq=gwenfritz%20moved&pg=PT126#v=snippet&q=gwenfritz&f=false| title=Going public| publisher= Arts Extension Service| year= 1988| isbn= 978-0-945464-00-6 | editor= Pam Korza }} \n*http://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/the-gwenfritz-by-alexander-calder/\n*http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM9CXY_Gwenfritz_Washington_DC\n*http://siris-sihistory.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!sichronology&uri=full=3100001~!9319~!0#focus\n\n{{Alexander Calder}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gwenfritz}}\n[[Category:Sculptures by Alexander Calder]]\n[[Category:1968 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of the Smithsonian Institution]]\n[[Category:Abstract sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Steel sculptures in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Northwest (Washington, D.C.)]]\n\n{{-}}\n{{sculpture-stub}}\n{{Smithsonian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Template:Public art in Washington, D.C.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gwenfritz"}
{"title_page": "Sachin Bansal", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian entrepreneur}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sachin Bansal\n| image              = Sachin Bansal.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1981|08|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chandigarh]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| alma_mater         = [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]]\n| occupation         = Chief Executive Officer of BAC Acquisitions Private Limited\n| net_worth          = [[United States dollar|$]] 1 billion<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite news |last=Ganjoo |first=Shweta |date=May 10, 2018 |title=Flipkart-Walmart deal: Sachin Bansal gets over Rs 6700 crore and leaves company, Binny Bansal staying back |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/technology/news/story/flipkart-walmart-deal-sachin-bansal-earns-over-rs-6700-crore-and-leaves-company-binny-bansal-staying-back-1229434-2018-05-09 |work=India Today |location=New Delhi |access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><small>(May 10, 2018)</small>\n| known_for          = [[Flipkart]]\n| title              = {{Unbulleted list|[[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of Flipkart|Executive Chairman of Flipkart}}\n| spouse             = Priya Bansal\n| parents            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Sachin Bansal''' (born August 5, 1981) is an Indian technology entrepreneur and an ardent gamer.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=ET Awards 2012-13: How IIT-alumnus Sachin Bansal built Flipkart into a big online brand | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/et-awards-2012-13-how-iit-alumnus-sachin-bansal-built-flipkart-into-a-big-online-brand/articleshow/23065635.cms |work=The Economic Times |agency=ET Bureau |date=September 26, 2013 |access-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web | date=October 6, 2014 |title= Sachin Bansal, Binny Bansal |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2014/10/06/sachin-bansal-binny-bansal.html |work=CNBC |access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> He is best known as the co-founder of [[Flipkart]] that was acquired by [[Walmart]] (77 per cent stakes) at $16 billion in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nair |first=Radhika |date=August 9, 2013 |title=Do not start alone, find a co-founder: Sachin Bansal, Flipkart |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/opinion/interviews/do-not-start-alone-find-a-co-founder-sachin-bansal-flipkart/articleshow/21719426.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> During his career at Flipkart that spanned 11 years, Bansal held the position of [[Chief Executive Officer]] and Executive [[Chairman]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |date=May 9, 2018 |title=Walmart\u2019s $16 billion Flipkart deal creates two billionaires |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/F0neES2FfrPuk5FGP9IOMO/Walmarts-16-billion-Flipkart-deal-creates-two-billionaires.html |work=Mint | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2018, Bansal exited Flipkart along with the Walmart deal.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite news | date=May 10, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal quits Flipkart as Walmart wanted only one founder on board |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/features/sachin-bansal-quits-flipkart-as-walmart-wanted-only-one-founder-on-board/articleshow/64103047.cms |work=The Economic Times |accessdate=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Sachin Bansal and [[Binny Bansal]] (not related) founded Flipkart whose valuation in 2018 was $20.8 billion.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In 2018, Bansal held 5.5 per cent stake in Flipkart, which he sold off to Walmart and his net worth then was a little over $1 billion.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In May 2018, Bansal announced that after stepping down as the Executive Chairman of Flipkart, he would be focusing on pending personal projects, gaming and brushing up his coding skills.<ref>{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | date=May 10, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal Will Catch up on Gaming, Personal Projects After Leaving Flipkart |url=https://www.news18.com/news/business/sachin-bansal-will-catch-up-on-gaming-personal-projects-after-leaving-flipkart-1743685.html |work=News 18 | agency=PTI | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBansal was born in [[Chandigarh]], India, on August 5, 1981.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> His father is a business man and mother, a homemaker.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Sachin Bansal \u2013 Life Story |url= http://cxopartners.in/sachin-bansal-life-story |work=CXO Partners | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> Bansal attended [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]] and completed a degree in Computer Engineering in 2005.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> After graduation, Bansal worked at Techspan for a few months and later in 2006 he joined Amazon Web Services as a Senior Software Engineer.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://cxopartners.in/sachin-bansal-life-story |title=Sachin Bansal \u2013 Life Story |website=CXO Partners | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2007, Bansal quit Amazon to start his own venture.\n\n==Flipkart==\nIn October 2007, Bansal and his co-founder, Binny Bansal, started an online bookstore, Flipkart, with an initial capital of \u20b9400,000 (US$5,600).<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news | date=May 10, 2018 |title=When Flipkart Co-Founder Sachin Bansal Had To Return Amazon Employee Recommendation Bonus |url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/when-flipkart-co-founder-sachin-bansal-had-to-return-amazon-employee-recommendation-bonus-1850216 |work=NDTV | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> They first started operating out of an apartment in Koramangala, in [[Bangalore]], India. In the first few months, according to Bansal's own claims, he oversaw all business details, from building the first version of their website to sourcing book to packing and delivering them.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> From inception until 2016, Bansal held the position of Chief Executive Officer and from 2016 until 2018, he held the position of Executive Chairman.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2018, Bansal signed a non-compete clause with Walmart and exited Flipkart.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news | date=May 12, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal: From outsized Flipkart presence to outcast  |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/7TpoCOdT6RSoRlVVeZyptJ/Sachin-Bansals-changing-fortunes-From-outsized-Flipkart-pr.html |work=Mint | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\"/> The non-compete clause restricted Bansal from starting any business that directly or indirectly competed with Flipkart for 18 months and in making any investments in businesses competing with Flipkart for 36 months from his departure.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n== Post-Flipkart ==\nIn December 2018, Bansal founded BAC Acquisitions Private Limited, a venture that focused on building and acquiring technology-driven businesses in diverse industry verticals.<ref>{{cite news | date=December 24, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal kicks off new venture BAC Acquisitions close to first Flipkart office | url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/startups/sachin-bansal-kicks-off-new-venture-bac-acquisitions-close-to-first-flipkart-office/67232357 |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> Since 2014, Bansal has made 18 investments in local, early-stage startups where the deal size was $1\u20132 million.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news | date=February 20, 2019 |title=Flipkart co-founder Sachin Bansal invests Rs 650 crore in Ola |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/flipkart-co-founder-sachin-bansal-invests-rs-650-crore-in-ola/articleshow/68062559.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2019, Bansal invested $100 million in [[Ola Cabs]] and received a stake holding of 0.37 per cent.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news | date=January 19, 2019 |title=Sachin Bansal invests $100 mn in Ola in boost for Bhavish Aggarwal |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/keHGGkLpfiI2WacfOCysCI/Sachin-Bansal-buys-stake-in-Bhavish-Aggarwals-Ola.html |work=Mint | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Peermohamed |first=Alnoor | date=January 15, 2019 |title=Sachin Bansal hands a Rs 150-crore cheque to Ola as part of a larger funding round |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/sachin-bansal-invests-21-million-in-ola-as-part-of-a-larger-funding-round/articleshow/67524201.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In February 2019, he had investments in Ola, Grey Orange, Ather Energy, SigTuple, Inshorts, Unacademy and TeamIndus.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nSachin acquired the general insurance brand COCO, previously owned by the housing finance company deewan housing finance limited, through his company Navi technology in 2020\n\n==Recognition==\n* In 2013, Bansal was awarded the Economic Times Award - \u2018Entrepreneur of the year\u2019.<ref>{{cite news | date=September 26, 2013 |title=ET Awards 2012-13: How IIT-alumnus Sachin Bansal built Flipkart into a big online brand | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/et-awards-2012-13-how-iit-alumnus-sachin-bansal-built-flipkart-into-a-big-online-brand/articleshow/23065635.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> \n* In 2015, Bansal was named as the 86th richest person in India by Forbes India.<ref>{{cite web |title=#2057 Sachin Bansal | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/sachin-bansal/#3eaa1e1d2941 |website=Forbes | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n* In 2016, Time Magazine included Bansal and his co-founder in the 100 most influential people in the world list.<ref>{{cite news | date=April 22, 2016 |title=Flipkart's Sachin & Binny Bansal among Time's 100 most influential people in the world | url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/people/flipkarts-sachin-binny-bansal-among-times-100-most-influential-people-in-the-world/51936156 |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n* In 2017, India Today included Bansal and his co-founder in India's 50 most powerful people list.<ref>{{cite news | date=April 14, 2017 |title=50 power people | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/20170424-india-today-top-50-powerful-indians-mukesh-ambani-ratan-tata-kumar-mangalam-birla-gautam-adani-anand-mahindra-srk-amitabh-bacchan-986203-2017-04-14 |work=India Today | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSachin Bansal is married to,Priya Bansal a dentist by training and profession.<ref>{{cite news | date=August 21, 2017 |title=Power couples at the ET Start-up Awards 2017: Sachin and Priya Bansal, Neetha and Sriharsha Majety, and more | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/power-couples-at-the-et-start-up-awards-2017-sachin-andpriya-bansal-neetha-and-sriharsha-majety-and-more/articleshow/60152020.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | date=March 7, 2016 |title=Here Are The Women Behind India\u2019s 11 Top Startup Stars | url=https://officechai.com/startups/wives-of-indian-startup-founders/ |work=Office Chai  | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> They have one son.<ref name=\"auto9\"/>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn March 2020, Sachin Bansal's wife Priya Bansal filed a dowry harassment case against him alleging physical assault and pressure to transfer properties to his name.\nShe also alleged that Sachin sexually assaulted her sister.A First Information Report registered at the Koramangala police station on February 28 named four persons, including Sachin's parents Sat Prakash Agarwal and Kiran Bansal and brother Nitin Bansal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/flipkart-sachin-bansal-family-dowry-harassment-case_in_5e6092e8c5b69d641c0aa796|title=Flipkart Co-Founder Sachin Bansal, His Family Accused Of Dowry Harassment By Wife Priya|date=2020-03-05|website=HuffPost India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bansal, Sachin}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian software engineers]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Amazon.com people]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian Internet company founders]]\n[[Category:Indian online retailer founders]]\n[[Category:Flipkart people]]\n[[Category:Indian computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Indian technology company founders]]\n[[Category:Indian technology chief executives]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian entrepreneur}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sachin Bansal\n| image              = Sachin Bansal.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1981|08|05}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chandigarh]], India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| alma_mater         = [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]]\n| occupation         = Chief Executive Officer of BAC Acquisitions Private Limited\n| net_worth          = [[United States dollar|$]] 1 billion<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite news |last=Ganjoo |first=Shweta |date=May 10, 2018 |title=Flipkart-Walmart deal: Sachin Bansal gets over Rs 6700 crore and leaves company, Binny Bansal staying back |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/technology/news/story/flipkart-walmart-deal-sachin-bansal-earns-over-rs-6700-crore-and-leaves-company-binny-bansal-staying-back-1229434-2018-05-09 |work=India Today |location=New Delhi |access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><small>(May 10, 2018)</small>\n| known_for          = [[Flipkart]]\n| title              = {{Unbulleted list|[[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of Flipkart|Executive Chairman of Flipkart}}\n| spouse             = Priya Bansal\n| parents            = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Sachin Bansal''' (born August 5, 1981) is an Indian technology entrepreneur and an ardent gamer.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=ET Awards 2012-13: How IIT-alumnus Sachin Bansal built Flipkart into a big online brand | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/et-awards-2012-13-how-iit-alumnus-sachin-bansal-built-flipkart-into-a-big-online-brand/articleshow/23065635.cms |work=The Economic Times |agency=ET Bureau |date=September 26, 2013 |access-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web | date=October 6, 2014 |title= Sachin Bansal, Binny Bansal |url= https://www.cnbc.com/2014/10/06/sachin-bansal-binny-bansal.html |work=CNBC |access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> He is best known as the co-founder of [[Flipkart]] that was acquired by [[Walmart]] (77 per cent stakes) at $16 billion in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nair |first=Radhika |date=August 9, 2013 |title=Do not start alone, find a co-founder: Sachin Bansal, Flipkart |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/opinion/interviews/do-not-start-alone-find-a-co-founder-sachin-bansal-flipkart/articleshow/21719426.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> During his career at Flipkart that spanned 11 years, Bansal held the position of [[Chief Executive Officer]] and Executive [[Chairman]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |date=May 9, 2018 |title=Walmart\u2019s $16 billion Flipkart deal creates two billionaires |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/F0neES2FfrPuk5FGP9IOMO/Walmarts-16-billion-Flipkart-deal-creates-two-billionaires.html |work=Mint | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2018, Bansal exited Flipkart along with the Walmart deal.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite news | date=May 10, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal quits Flipkart as Walmart wanted only one founder on board |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/features/sachin-bansal-quits-flipkart-as-walmart-wanted-only-one-founder-on-board/articleshow/64103047.cms |work=The Economic Times |accessdate=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Sachin Bansal and [[Binny Bansal]] (not related) founded Flipkart whose valuation in 2018 was $20.8 billion.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In 2018, Bansal held 5.5 per cent stake in Flipkart, which he sold off to Walmart and his net worth then was a little over $1 billion.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In May 2018, Bansal announced that after stepping down as the Executive Chairman of Flipkart, he would be focusing on pending personal projects, gaming and brushing up his coding skills.<ref>{{cite news | author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | date=May 10, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal Will Catch up on Gaming, Personal Projects After Leaving Flipkart |url=https://www.news18.com/news/business/sachin-bansal-will-catch-up-on-gaming-personal-projects-after-leaving-flipkart-1743685.html |work=News 18 | agency=PTI | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBansal was born in [[Chandigarh]], India, on August 5, 1981.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> His father is a business man and mother, a homemaker.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Sachin Bansal \u2013 Life Story |url= http://cxopartners.in/sachin-bansal-life-story |work=CXO Partners | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> Bansal attended [[Indian Institute of Technology Delhi]] and graduated as a Computer Science engineer in 2005.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> During the course of his education, Bansal had considered giving up his engineering seat to pursue a career in gaming.<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite news | date=September 6, 2018 |title= Flipkart-Walmart deal changed Sachin Bansal's life, brought him closer to family |url= https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/flipkart-walmart-deal-changed-sachin-bansals-life-brought-him-closer-to-family/articleshow/65695220.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> [[Age of Empires]] and [[Quake III Arena]] are the games that he was playing in his early life.<ref name=\"auto9\"/> After graduation, Bansal worked at Techspan for a few months and later in 2006 he joined Amazon Web Services as a Senior Software Engineer.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://cxopartners.in/sachin-bansal-life-story |title=Sachin Bansal \u2013 Life Story |website=CXO Partners | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2007, Bansal quit Amazon to start his own venture.\n\n==Flipkart==\nIn October 2007, Bansal and his co-founder, Binny Bansal, started an online bookstore, Flipkart, with an initial capital of \u20b9400,000 (US$5,600).<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite news | date=May 10, 2018 |title=When Flipkart Co-Founder Sachin Bansal Had To Return Amazon Employee Recommendation Bonus |url=https://www.ndtv.com/business/when-flipkart-co-founder-sachin-bansal-had-to-return-amazon-employee-recommendation-bonus-1850216 |work=NDTV | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> They first started operating out of an apartment in Koramangala, in [[Bangalore]], India. In the first few months, according to Bansal's own claims, he oversaw all business details, from building the first version of their website to sourcing book to packing and delivering them.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> From inception until 2016, Bansal held the position of Chief Executive Officer and from 2016 until 2018, he held the position of Executive Chairman.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2018, Bansal signed a non-compete clause with Walmart and exited Flipkart.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite news | date=May 12, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal: From outsized Flipkart presence to outcast  |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/7TpoCOdT6RSoRlVVeZyptJ/Sachin-Bansals-changing-fortunes-From-outsized-Flipkart-pr.html |work=Mint | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\"/> The non-compete clause restricted Bansal from starting any business that directly or indirectly competed with Flipkart for 18 months and in making any investments in businesses competing with Flipkart for 36 months from his departure.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n== Post-Flipkart ==\nIn December 2018, Bansal founded BAC Acquisitions Private Limited, a venture that focused on building and acquiring technology-driven businesses in diverse industry verticals.<ref>{{cite news | date=December 24, 2018 |title=Sachin Bansal kicks off new venture BAC Acquisitions close to first Flipkart office | url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/startups/sachin-bansal-kicks-off-new-venture-bac-acquisitions-close-to-first-flipkart-office/67232357 |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> Since 2014, Bansal has made 18 investments in local, early-stage startups where the deal size was $1\u20132 million.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news | date=February 20, 2019 |title=Flipkart co-founder Sachin Bansal invests Rs 650 crore in Ola |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/flipkart-co-founder-sachin-bansal-invests-rs-650-crore-in-ola/articleshow/68062559.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In 2019, Bansal invested $100 million in [[Ola Cabs]] and received a stake holding of 0.37 per cent.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite news | date=January 19, 2019 |title=Sachin Bansal invests $100 mn in Ola in boost for Bhavish Aggarwal |url=https://www.livemint.com/Companies/keHGGkLpfiI2WacfOCysCI/Sachin-Bansal-buys-stake-in-Bhavish-Aggarwals-Ola.html |work=Mint | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Peermohamed |first=Alnoor | date=January 15, 2019 |title=Sachin Bansal hands a Rs 150-crore cheque to Ola as part of a larger funding round |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/sachin-bansal-invests-21-million-in-ola-as-part-of-a-larger-funding-round/articleshow/67524201.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> In February 2019, he had investments in Ola, Grey Orange, Ather Energy, SigTuple, Inshorts, Unacademy and TeamIndus.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nSachin acquired the general insurance brand COCO, previously owned by the housing finance company deewan housing finance limited, through his company Navi technology in 2020\n\n==Recognition==\n* In 2013, Bansal was awarded the Economic Times Award - \u2018Entrepreneur of the year\u2019.<ref>{{cite news | date=September 26, 2013 |title=ET Awards 2012-13: How IIT-alumnus Sachin Bansal built Flipkart into a big online brand | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/et-awards-2012-13-how-iit-alumnus-sachin-bansal-built-flipkart-into-a-big-online-brand/articleshow/23065635.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> \n* In 2015, Bansal was named as the 86th richest person in India by Forbes India.<ref>{{cite web |title=#2057 Sachin Bansal | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/sachin-bansal/#3eaa1e1d2941 |website=Forbes | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n* In 2016, Time Magazine included Bansal and his co-founder in the 100 most influential people in the world list.<ref>{{cite news | date=April 22, 2016 |title=Flipkart's Sachin & Binny Bansal among Time's 100 most influential people in the world | url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/people/flipkarts-sachin-binny-bansal-among-times-100-most-influential-people-in-the-world/51936156 |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n* In 2017, India Today included Bansal and his co-founder in India's 50 most powerful people list.<ref>{{cite news | date=April 14, 2017 |title=50 power people | url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/cover-story/story/20170424-india-today-top-50-powerful-indians-mukesh-ambani-ratan-tata-kumar-mangalam-birla-gautam-adani-anand-mahindra-srk-amitabh-bacchan-986203-2017-04-14 |work=India Today | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSachin Bansal is married to,Priya Bansal a dentist by training and profession.<ref>{{cite news | date=August 21, 2017 |title=Power couples at the ET Start-up Awards 2017: Sachin and Priya Bansal, Neetha and Sriharsha Majety, and more | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/power-couples-at-the-et-start-up-awards-2017-sachin-andpriya-bansal-neetha-and-sriharsha-majety-and-more/articleshow/60152020.cms |work=The Economic Times | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | date=March 7, 2016 |title=Here Are The Women Behind India\u2019s 11 Top Startup Stars | url=https://officechai.com/startups/wives-of-indian-startup-founders/ |work=Office Chai  | access-date=April 8, 2019 }}</ref> They have one son.<ref name=\"auto9\"/>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn March 2020, Sachin Bansal's wife Priya Bansal filed a dowry harassment case against him alleging physical assault and pressure to transfer properties to his name.\nShe also alleged that Sachin sexually assaulted her sister.A First Information Report registered at the Koramangala police station on February 28 named four persons, including Sachin's parents Sat Prakash Agarwal and Kiran Bansal and brother Nitin Bansal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/flipkart-sachin-bansal-family-dowry-harassment-case_in_5e6092e8c5b69d641c0aa796|title=Flipkart Co-Founder Sachin Bansal, His Family Accused Of Dowry Harassment By Wife Priya|date=2020-03-05|website=HuffPost India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bansal, Sachin}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian software engineers]]\n[[Category:Indian Institute of Technology Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Amazon.com people]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian Internet company founders]]\n[[Category:Indian online retailer founders]]\n[[Category:Flipkart people]]\n[[Category:Indian computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Indian technology company founders]]\n[[Category:Indian technology chief executives]]\n", "name_user": "Cokestunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:hobbies are not relevant to wiki BLP. Also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sachin_Bansal"}
